Morning track with Ben. He did 3 minute reps and mine was 2x600, 1x 800, 600, 400, 2x 200 and 400 all with walking recovery.
column5: Track a bit crowded with walkers in lane 1. The Police Academy trainees were very polite and moved to lane 2 And 3. My second 200 I had to dodge some walkers that stopped for a photo op and took up lanes 1 through 4  overall happy with the workout!

column3: Little Falls easy double with a good crew. Talked about chili for a little bit
Afternoon Ride to grab some books for the summer school kiddos. Thanks Aubrey!
Morning Run easy at the track and some strides while Ry, Dan, Dave, and Joe did some repeats.
column5: Soft track felt great and I tried out some EnduroX courtesy of Dave. Looks like I'll be adding it to my training

column3: Morning Run easy up and down then some 200s with minute recovery. Sweaty today
Morning Run head and sinus are still bothering me. Maybe that's why this felt like I was about to pass out the last 3 miles
Morning Walk barefoot eyes closed light headed stumbling on the sidewalk
Afternoon Run easy up and down! Last hills before Boilermaker!
Morning Run 2 x 1000 with 3 minute walk between. Feeling pretty good for Sunday
Morning Run heart rate progression through easy and into a bit of effort with the dudes  finished with some strides
column5: Met up with Joe, Paul, and Dave. They did pace work and I progressed the heart rate up slowly. Felt really good and, you'll think I'm crazy, but surprisingly cool...not really cranking the pace though so.... pretty darn optimistic for Sunday!

column3: Enchanted Forest with family!  Photos coming soon
Morning Shakeout and strides with Sneaker Store! Great to see all your awesome faces! Let's rock tomorrow!
Got the bib and saw even more great faces!
Driving range with the fam! What a great day!
Maker warm up to see the band! Love my brothers and sister! Nikki and Mike they miss you! Look for SOUNDBARRIER right after mile 2!
Boilermaker 2024 more pics and vids coming! So happy with the results! PB for the course!
Walk out of the med tent. No IV this year! Just some rest in a chair and some water and Gatorade
Pool at Tom's! Helluva good time, love this group!

column5: 4 easy > 3 to get heart up to 150 > 1 down > 1 sort of effort. Nice!
3 easy > 1 heart up to 150 > 1 down

column3: Evening Run easy SSSRC with a nice water stop!
Morning Run easy 30 minutes. Meeting with marathon Coach Karen later. Then maybe an easy double before dark!

column5:
Day 1


3 easy > 3 up > bout 2.5 down


Warm was huffin a bit, nothing I couldn't keep down with keeping the heartrate low as recommended.


3 up felt great. A little too up on the first one pace wise, so feel like I should keep the heart rate lower as I begin this (maybe look at pace and go for 8:10-8:20 as I begin these?). Middle one felt great, last one was tough with tiny bit of climb. Again, felt like I started the 3 up too hot pace wise.


Cool down was perfect!
Nice pedal

column3: Morning run with Dave and Paul
column5:
Day 2 with Paul and Dave. Got the heart rate up more and felt good!

2 warm > 8 with HR between 130ish and 150ish

Plan was 10 in that HR ZONE but knowing the 5k is tomorrow and I'll be up with the band and have show responsibilities until about 10:30 tonight, I felt it was okay to cut the last 2 miles off.

Real happy with the HR considering I actually put some effort in on the uphills.

column3: Zoo Walk with Sarah and Cody!
Morning Run Sundae 5k route 20 series 3rd place age group!
column5:
Day 3

Felt great coming off Boilermaker and more effort miles this past week! Plus a 19 hour day yesterday up late with the band and on 6 hours sleep  Right amount of effort, maybe could have gone stronger on the start or at the finish. Had to hold myself up on the dude at the finish who was taking tags off for timing, and felt I could have gone a bit deeper into a harder pace, so there's room for improvement. Feel like 4 x mile repeats at 6:40/:50 with 3 minute recovery could be a good way to get that upper limit tested. 

Feeling confident going into Tunnel to Towers and Run 4 River Half 

Cheers to all the great runners today, and Maeve's sticker had another finish!

column3: Day 4 Afternoon chi running setting the form and falling forward while feeling tall
Afternoon Ride to the park and back home!
Afternoon Run warm up for endurance 8
column5: Felt good, falling forward with chi

Set the chi form and just started falling. Felt REALLY good and even was able to adjust the chi during the run. Felt strong and seemed to be able to maintain pace and heart rate better than usual. The cool down was almost perfect, felt a little disconnected. Was wearing pro 2s so that definitely helps. Tomorrow I want to run on the slower end of endurance.
Love getting right out of the sneakers
Felt real good! Falling forward much better.

That got tough at the end! Felt tall and knew I was heating up as the pace ended up on the higher end of endurance. Overall good feeling and gotta manage the pace and heart rate better tomorrow for endurance 8. Cool down was appropriate, I was pretty hot at the end

Day 7 NYC Marathon training

Felt really refreshed when I woke up today considering yesterday was pretty tough. No fatigue in the hips or quads. I've been rolling out most nights, about 5 minutes each leg. Run was spot on and focused. Was going for middle to slower end of endurance range, and pretty much ended up in the middle with a bit of the faster end. Great start and mile 6 felt great with that bit of climb! Tough but in control. Falling forward and feeling tall!

Cool down felt appropriate, just falling forward and brought the heart rate down.

column3: Afternoon Ride Day 8 NYC Marathon training
column5: Nice to keep the legs moving and no impact. Good to see the city on pedals.

column3: Morning Run warm up to the track super cool temps! Felt good falling forward
Morning Workout drills. Heel walks, balls of foot walks, that thing where you raise your knees and double tap your foot (I don't know what it's called ) and a stride.
column5: Drills. Heel walks, balls of foot walks, that thing where you raise your knees and double tap your foot (I don't know what it's called ) and a stride.

column3: Day 9 NYC Marathon training with Chris for a bit
column5:
Chris went long and did some of his steady state at the track while I zipped around. He was looking strong and it was cool to cross paths every so often. I've done this a few times and it's kinda fun to do different stuff at the track while others are doing their thing.

This was 5 x 6 minutes at around 6:50/mile with about 1:30 walking recovery then set the chi form and jog into the start of the next rep to bring total rest to 2 minutes. Cool down was excellent, just falling forward and super easy.

Felt very strong and as if the pace was right where it should be as I was going for about 8k pace. Maybe could have pushed a little more on the pace, but wanted to feel comfortably strong. I might want to try this workout again, but combine the 3rd and 4th rep into a 12 minute stretch with a 3 or 4 minute recovery. Thoughts?

I think on this trajectory I should be sub 20 for the T2T 5k and the Run 4 River half marathon should be around a 1:32ish. 

Gonna go long tomorrow, possibly 20. Thinking 12 VERY EASY 9 to 10 minutes pace. Then 6 at endurance 8 to 9 minutes pace steady or progression, and see how I'm feeling for the last 2 miles.

Overall very happy so far

column3: Walk to get some cremeria shakes and affagato
Day 10 Morning Run, wanted 20....Sarah picked me up
column5:
Literally exploded after the initial climb up oxford and into the flat part. Overheated started to see double and anxiety set in. 

Everything up to that felt great, and thinking back on it right now as I'm walking back home I went way too fast down Roberts Road. I should have been about a minute to a minute and a half slower closer to 9:30 or 10 minute Pace and then on the flats coming off of Holman City same thing. Should have been 9:30. Just should have kept it easy. And then enter the endurance zone once I maybe settled into the flatter part of Oxford, maybe by Kellogg Road or by New Hartford high School. So it was a learning experience and I think coming off of all those endurance miles last week I can't beat myself up over this. I'm at 50 something miles for the week so that's awesome. Rest tomorrow!!!!

Also, maybe that was the way that run was supposed to go. I had a lot of early miles in the endurance zone granted they were downhill. I'll reflect more this afternoon when I'm not seeing double
Hopped around to see if I could get the 5 miles back home to hit 20. No effin way

column3: Morning walk to get Boilermaker free Gatorade

column5:
This all felt great. Nice climb up in the switchbacks then flat at the end to MV and back. Last miles were so good! Was keeping HR around 135 and was basically around 9 minutes pace. Especially happy after all the massive climbing up Graffenburg on Sunday.

Looks like the fartlek could be an option tomorrow.

I'm wondering about Wednesday and Sunday or Saturday workouts/uptempo, and then slowly putting endurance miles into the big Saturday or Sunday runs (18 to 20 miles with 13 or 14 VERY easy then up the pace a bit for the last miles).

Warm up was good. Drills were a bit shocking! And the strides were a little bit shocking after the 2-mile warm up.

I did lunge matrix and leg swings. Didn't get to A skips or B skips. Did 10 reps of each.

The fartlek felt great. All the paces were a bit hot but everything felt fine and the 200 recovery at a much slower pace was great. Then stretching afterwards as usual.

I think overall a great workout and I'm looking forward to managing the endurance runs throughout the week and looking forward to the long run and pacing it much much better. 

As I'm sitting down at home I can feel different muscles woke up with the drills it seems. Nice!

column3: Day 13 New York City marathon training
column5:
8 easy miles based on heart rate. Felt good. Apparently what I thought was fatigue in my quads was just them being engaged? I did not feel like my quads were working hard. The heart rate was manageable, and the climbs were great. Finished with some leg swings in addition to the usual hydration and stretching!


Rest tomorrow, maybe ride the bike for a half hour flat. Just enough to keep the legs moving a little bit.


Feeling good after this past Sunday and looking forward to a much more managed long run this weekend!
Feels so good to just pedal enough to move the bike on the flats. Quads feel great!

column3: Day 15 NYC Marathon Training with Joe, Paul, Craig and Dave for a bit
column5:
I'm exhausted. Was supposed to be 16 miles. Will make some notes later, but initial thoughts are I had zero rest and recovery after Boilermaker, went right into the 5k the next weekend, then miles at a faster pace then I typically ever run for 6 to 8 miles in a row. I think I'm very used to running with my heart between 125 and 135 and that the higher heart rate is shocking my system. Maybe a bit of a reset is in order.

Last summer I couldn't walk after Boilermaker for about a week and ran super slow up until September, granted I didn't have a marathon coming up  so I'm not sure what I need besides good old fashioned rest
It's okay, I'm fine. Need a reset! I think some more easy 125 to 135 HR steady runs.

Incredible! Incredible, incredible! Felt so good! Just kept my heart rate under 125 for a while and the last 2 miles felt awesome. 5 strides at the end felt great. Granted there was way less humidity and I had vaporflys on (whatever I felt awesome and needed the confidence boosy ), I felt so much more in control because I went very easy for about the first 80% of that run.


I kind of want to do the same thing tomorrow. Just maybe amp up the last 2 miles a little more I don't know. We'll see. I think holding my heart rate steady at 130 to 140 in this type of temperature and humidity could be very beneficial and then steady 140 to 145 for the last miles.

 Thinking back to Saturday, I would say my heart rate should have been no higher than 130 and then get it up to 135-140 and hold steady. I was approaching 150 and even over 150 too soon and that just cooked me.

Learning every day! Love it!

column3: Day 17 NYC Marathon Training 5 x 3 min CV/300m
column5:
Pretty good workout! Some of the paces were hot but everything felt controlled and managed and nothing was all out, especially the 300m repeats.


Warm up and cool down were exactly on. Didn't care about pace it was all about keeping the heart rate easy.

Big climb up Graffenburg, across Higby, down Valley View, then some of miles 4 and 5 of Boilermaker.

Felt fantastic. So much less humidity, and I have to remember to keep my HR low next time it's humid.

Gonna go more flat tomorrow looks like? Maybe another climb. I love slow climbing 

Excited for the weekend long run/workout.

Kept heart rate low again and kept it relatively flat with a couple small climbs on the back of MV. 

Feels like I'm right where I should be considering the weather being incredibly cool compared to last week!

Finished with 5 strides.

Fifth rep was really tough. I had to walk after that last rep. I was on the edge. Stopped for some Gatorade, and then couldn't get back up to any decent pace to finish out so I just did what my body felt and it was fine. Also, didn't want to get too fatigued knowing I've got miles tomorrow too, and should hit around 60ish for the week. Basically walked/jogged after last rep. Stopped and talked with Bill P. He had some cool mushroom foraging stories.


Overall very pleased considering what ended up happening the past two weekends. I'm feeling very confident if I had to just go out and run 20 or 22 miles easy based on low HR.
Fantastic! Even felt my foot strike and arm swing making tiny adjustments. Will make some more notes later, but for now felt excellent and chi form is good!

A little more humid and muggy, but felt fantastic. Same feeling in the arm swings and foot strike, and adjusted well to the small climbs. Heart got up a little bit higher, but nothing crazy and still in the right zones.


Really excited for Tunnel to Towers 5K on Sunday. A great cause, and looking to PR for 5k!

Solid run warm up was perfect. Maybe progressed a little bit too quickly during the warm up, but I think it was fine.


Probably could have taken the first two MP miles a little bit slower, but overall felt really strong.


Thinking Marathon race strategy might be hold 8:00 for 16 miles. Then 7 miles at 7:50. Then last 5K just go? Some food for thought!

Felt pretty strong. Maybe a bit too hot of a pace on the downhill, but holding the HR up a bit higher was manageable! 

Finished with a lunge matrix.

Looking forward to some rest tomorrow, easy on Saturday, then racing Tunnel 2 Towers 5k on Sunday.

Felt pretty weak. My HR got right up to the upper limit of the range pretty quick and was just doing my best to slow down and keep it right Around 138 or so. I had a 20 hour day yesterday with work, a show at night, total time sitting and driving of 5 hours, and it was fairly humid. A lot of factors, but I'll get some good rest tonight for sure!

Still positive for tomorrow!

column3: A little walking and A skips
A little more warm up T2T

column5:
Tunnel to Towers 5k! Great event for an amazing cause! Maeve's sticker gets another finish!

Of course I PR 5k and run 20:03 was really hoping for sub 20, but I almost needed a medic at the end. Been definitely leaving it all out there these past races and going deep into redline. Onward!

column3: Cool down and a bit of volume added on for the day

column5: That was awesome. It helped that it was basically freezing out compared to the humidity we've had Also went ahead and wore Pro 2s because felt like easing back down from the elites yesterday. Will probably go with speed 3s tomorrow. Arm swings felt super on and locked in, and experimented a bit with just thinking about the knees being pulled up higher like they're on strings (A skips video info). Could definitely feel it in good combination with the chi form. Finished with a lunge matrix. Really excited for the next 2 weeks!

Felt amazing. This lack of humidity and cooler temps are helping quite a bit, but I'm thinking fitness is definitely on an upswing! Wore Pro 2s again cause why not. They feel awesome. Arm swings are really improving with the chi torso form. Finished with leg swings and lunge matrix. 5 to 8 reps each.


I've been watching lots of Ingibritsen. His arm swings and general "broadness" of upper body are other world. Maybe I'm just overall excited about the way things are going, but I think these small adjustments to form have changed my running in a major positive direction.

SSRC! Fantastic feel. Went out on my own then met up with Edick, Joe, Barry, and Josh B. Arm swings in full effect and the demo'd Asics "something blast". They felt great.

Awesome climb up Woodberry through the old neighborhood then down by the high school. Finished with a lunge matrix (5 reps each) then a nice beer and bit of food at Grow Brewery.

 If anyone's missing a cat, just ask Edick  not for real, just a great joke he played on his son while he was talking to him on the phone during the run

This was the planned run. Felt great and met up with Ben Nelson (I can't tag him ). He's gonna rock a fall half marathon and doesn't even know it yet. A little bit warmer today and GPS didn't kick in until about 2 minutes in, so actual pace was maybe about 8:35ish? Anyway, felt great and strides were strong. 

Finished with leg swings at a graduated rate from small swing to full swing then back down again. Then lunge matrix 3 to 4 reps each set. 

Mine and Sarah's 5 year anniversary weekend coming up

column3: Day 30 NYC Marathon Training and mine and Sarah's 5th WEDDING ANNIVERSARY!
column5:
That was pretty good! First rep to settle in then reps 2 through 4 were on. That last float was tough. Really had to get myself back down. Felt like I went into the pain cave for some solid portions of this. Strides felt great and could have gone for a longer cool down, but wanted to stick close to the planned mileage. I'm pretty excited for next weekend's half marathon! 

Finished with lunge matrix and leg swings. Now time to enjoy more of our anniversary around Old Forge

column3: Morning walk at McCauley with Sarah
column5: Closed for a private event and construction  Still fun to see the base of the mountain though!
Beautiful! Sad to leave, but happy to see our kitty Kats at home!
Felt really good and loose! Finished with a lunge matrix, 5 reps each. Excited for a few days this week before the half on Saturday!

Little trot around then finished with lunge matrix 3 reps each and leg swings.

Had a great meeting with Coach Karen at Sneaker Store, prior. We're doing great with the training! Got some cool insights.

I feel like this was right on, but the pace range had me psyched out a bit. My HR got higher than I expected but was very manageable! Maybe a bit overreaching? My gut instinct says to back off a bit more for tomorrow's 8 miles. We shall see! Feeling very good for the half marathon this weekend.

I don't know. I felt kinda whooped after this. Maybe I'm more fit than I think? I kinda don't like being in this position because I can't tell if I'm overreaching or if my body can actually handle this "fatigue". I can't tell if I'm fatigued or my body is just adjusting and getting more fit. My HR was way higher than I thought it would be for this pace, but I guess my body handled it fine? Not sure, lots of guessing and maybe I'm overthinking it all. I did spend 4 hours climbing a ladder and painting the exterior of a house today, so there's that  Finished with lunge matrix 3 reps each.
Felt good! Finished with a lunge matrix 5 reps each. Cooler temps helped!
Fatigue and some psychological factors crept in. Terrible combination. I just did what I could. Really supportive group to help and talk afterward

Hills for tempo. First 10 minutes was a 250 foot climb. Second 10 minutes was about 150 up then came back down about 50 feet maybe. I love hills. I was instantly focused and breathing sharply around the 6 to 8 minutes mark of the second 10 minutes effort, and felt so focused and strong. I missed the hills and I feel confident with my HR and effort driving the run. 

Finished with a lunge matrix 3 reps each.

This felt so goddam good. HR and hills. Switchbacks then 4 strides, lunge matrix 5 reps each, and leg swings. I feel great focusing on the HR and love the shift back to this style of training. It feels so good to set pace aside and get cerebral about my effort and HR.

Forgot yesterday the Mexican wolves were HOWLING in the Utica Zoo around sunset. Amazing how one starts off, slowly join in the howl one by one and howl slightly out of tune, then gradually get in tune 

Anyway, tonight was about 600 foot of climb on this. Felt awesome just locked into effort and HR! I used to do this route a ton, Golf hill to the SOS easy hill repeats then up to the Eagle. Finished with lunge matrix 5 reps and leg swings.

Felt so good. Slow slow slow and on HR. I cried at the end I was so happy to do 20 again. Huge climbs nature was great. Even stopped and drank from a stream! Ran with Tim and Dave for a bit. Great route thanks guys!

800 feet of climbing in this one. 2 Steele Hills and 4 SOS hills, then 4 strides. Lots of dog walkers and families out  Finished with lunge matrix 5 reps each and leg swings. Real excited for the MAF/HR style training!

Wow, I've never felt that before. Sharp focus and intense for the last mile of that. Locked in, but couldn't get the HR up into that last chunk. I feel like I could have, but above 165 is wild for me! Had it at about 163 for the last half mile. This was possibly the best workout I've ever done, and all based on HR  and effort. I'm so excited for the rest of the week. Easy hills on HR and effort. Finished with lunge matrix 5 reps each and leg swings.
Nice climbing! Had a few 98 HR Putney moments SOS easy hills tomorrow.
About 1000 foot of climb. Golf Hill, 7 SOS hills and then to the eagle. Finished with 4 strides and lunge matrix 5 reps each. Felt solid and in control. All HR

column3: Birthday run! Day 46 NYC Marathon Training
column5: Started the birthday with 20 miles. Absolutely love this route. Sunrise was gorgeous, someone has a pet pot bellied pig, and the views are astonishing the top of Graffenburg and Roberts and Mohawk. HR train is rolling. Got down to 85 BPM at one point. Locked in to effort and HR. Finished with lunge matrix 3 reps each and leg swings.

Golf hill, SOS, Eagle, then 4 strides. Great day out! Beautiful views all over. Finished with lunge matrix 5 reps each and leg swings.

Gotta think about a race between now and NYC. My band's playing falling leaves after party! So no go on that, but there are a few other 5ks about 5 or 6 weeks out, and a half marathon 3 weeks out. The half marathon would be a workout, wouldn't really race it. Just go on effort and HR, and would be nice to get some adrenaline going in a race atmosphere. Food for thought!

Felt awesome, HR based quality session. Excited for a big volume week! Feel like 135 to 140 HR might be good for the marathon? Maybe go out and attack one of the 20 milers a bit more aggressive on HR? Food for thought! Finished with lunge matrix 3 reps and leg swings.
Beautiful climb, wore a long sleeve. It was more humid than reported for sure! HR stress was spot on
Felt good considering the heat! Easy HR switchbacks and finished with lunge matrix 5 reps.

column3: Day 51 Sneaker Store NYC Marathon Training for Special Olympics NY
column5:
hrTSS 188! I'm thrilled! 2 weeks ago I ran 20 miles in 3:50:00ish, now 24 at 3:30:15 wore Nike alpha fly 1s and about 950 foot of climb throughout. 150 footer at mile 6, 150 footer at mile 14, then little 50 footers throughout. 

Kept it super in check up to mile 20 then ramped the HR up. Fueled every 4 miles (set up a little water station at the foot of my driveway ) 2 Maurten 160s, 2 Maurten 100s, and 2 Glukos lemon lime with caffeine. Stayed down super easy, so happy! Had the Maurtens safety pinned inside the waist band of my tights, and the 2 Glukos in the side pocket. Worked perfectly. Finished with lunge matrix 5 reps, these help a TON. No more lower back pain or tightness since I was introduced to them by Coach Karen 

Definitely doing the 5k next Saturday looks Iike. Will chat with Coach on Monday over the phone!
Great climb, double switchbacks. HR was spot on! Finished with lunge matrix 5 reps each and leg swings. Excited for Colie's 5k down in Richfield Springs this Saturday, looks like a fun one!

Eagle > Switchbacks > Eagle great climbs. Finished with 4 strides then SAM phase 1. These post run exercises are SICK courtesy of Coach Karen Sneaker Store HR spot on again. Excited to race the 5k this Saturday based on HR!
This was a fun one, might add on to this one next week or week after to make a 27 or 28 miler. Finished with lunge matrix 5 reps, a set of side steppers, and leg swings. Excited for Saturday's 5k!

Shakeout for tomorrow's 5k. HR strap glitched and spiked to 170 for the first half mile. True average was about 110 bpm. Strides then lunge matrix 3 reps each! Feeling good for an HR race tomorrow. Hit 4:15 pace on the last stride

Great event sponsored by Richfield Springs Fire Department. Started by a lady who used to run with her dog Colie who passed away.

Overall very happy with the first race based on heart rate even though I botched up the targets! Got way too high too soon. Especially with the back half of this course being a steady climb. Still 100% confident in the HR training, I need to remember to keep my heart rate lower than I think it should be at the beginning of all races from here on out. Also, the most refreshed I've felt a couple hours after a race. Granted I ran the slowest 5k I've ran in a while that doesn't matter, the marathon matters!

Dropped the car off for inspection tomorrow and then ran back to the neighborhood for a decent climb. Took a precision gel at mile 3 and a big gulp of water. Stayed down perfect, gotta get some more fueling done during some runs these next couple weeks. All systems go, 3 weeks then a 2 week taper looks like. Going for 20 this Wednesday then I'd like to shoot for 24 (maybe 27? ) on Saturday. Finished with lunge matrix 5 reps and SAM phase 1.
This felt amazing! HR train continues to roll! Took a precision 100mg caffeine gel at mile 3 and gulped 6 oz of water. Stayed down fine! Finished with lunge matrix 3 reps each and SAM phase 1

Did I get it right [strava://athletes/121758922/10]Ben Nelson ?  

Was supposed to run 8 tomorrow, but can't due to plans I forgot about. So I added onto today's planned 16. Some more fueling practice. Precision gel at 4 miles with a gulp of Gatorade and water. Gulp of Gatorade at mile 8. Precision again at mile 12 with a gulp of water. Precision caffeine gel at mile 16 with gulp of water. Not so sure how I feel about caffeine and MIGHT just stick with regular Precision gels. Finished with leg swings.

Felt awesome! Excited for 2 days of rest then looks like at least 24 on Saturday MAYBE 27, we'll see!

column3: Day 60 NYC  Training UNREAL HOW GOOD THIS FELT
column5:
Longest run ever. In complete control the whole time. All HR based, and Sneaker Store Coach Karen and I are going to deep dive an HR marathon strategy/goal! Been watching lots of Tamirat, his Paris run was flawless. He's in another world of meditation and relaxed focus that I've been trying to channel, and it came through today. Felt massive euphoria and "runners high" during most of this 

Fueled every 4 miles or so, took the precision caffeine at miles 4 and 16 and regular precision at 8, 12, 20 and 23. Caffeine is a go for race day, HR was unaffected. Stayed moving while i gulped water and Gatorade. Set up my hydration station at the foot of the driveway  Stomach kept everything down real easy! Finished with some leg swings and SAM phase 1. Now for some food

Eagle > Switchbacks > Eagle

Feel very fresh and ready to go for this week. Finished with a lunge matrix 5 reps. A little cut back on the distance of the long runs, then amp up for peak week next week.

7 more days until [strava://athletes/32985877/14]Clint Eastwood finds out! 

Locked in the whole time. The HR range continues to strengthen! Finished with lunge matrix 5 reps.
Great feeling the whole time  finished with lunge matrix 3 reps and leg swings.

Felt solid! Legs feel ready to fire in this HR range which I think is pretty good for about three and a half weeks out from the marathon Gonna chat with Coach Karen about peak week next week.... Three 20 milers?  We'll see! Finished with strides and SAM Phase 1

Planned on 24, but only getting 5 hours of sleep after a late band gig last night made me think it best to just cut after the HR ramp up with a short cool down. Felt solid!

I have a huge week coming up, three 20+ milers for peak. Monday, Wednesday, and Saturday.

Was nice to have [strava://athletes/121758922/10]Ben Nelson for the ramp up portion of the run today. He's in great shape for the Philly Half. Held somewhat of a conversation with him for the first portion of the ramp up, so that's really encouraging. I learned Osprey are out of season! 

Finished with leg swings and lunge matrix 5 reps. Fueled every 4 miles with precision (caffeine at mile 15). Gatorade and water station at the foot of the driveway.

Joe joined for some heart rate on a nice big one to start my week of three 20+ milers. Felt absolutely incredible and locked in the whole time. Last big 20+ of the block then a couple quality sessions this week within the last two 20 milers of the training block. Did I say 20 enough? 

Great conversations with Joe, we really enjoyed the scenery even though it was 4 mile loops and out and backs. Glad to have had him on the last big one. Fueled every 4 miles with precision (caffeine at miles 8 and 16) and Gatorade water station at the foot of the driveway. Those miles flew by! Big puddles too. Finished with leg swings and lunge matrix 5 reps.

column3: Day 67 NYC Marathon Training with Joe
column5:
Joe joined again for a heart rate run. Blasting some Zappa, Steely Dan, ELP, Dylan, Jethro Tull, so good! 

Unreal feeling, legs firing but with relaxed focus. Coach Karen with Sneaker Store Coaching wrote this genius workout, building strength and focus in higher HR ranges! Precision Gels every 4 miles (caffeine at 4 and 8). Water and Gatorade station at foot of driveway 

Finished with lunge matrix 5 reps and leg swings. Little shakeout tomorrow, then last 20 this Saturday

Felt great, excited for the last big quality day this Saturday! Legs will be ready to fire after the taper. Wore Alphafly 3 just to test them out. I'll have options for race day. Finished with SAM PHASE 1

column3: Day 69 NYC Marathon Training - HEART RATE MONSTER
column5:
Three 20s this week, took a note from the [strava://athletes/35670893/11]Dave Putney peak week bookThis one's for [strava://athletes/32985877/14]Clint Eastwood Day 69! Workout developed by Josh B at Sneaker Store, modified by Coach Karen for heart rate. Incredible feeling the whole time. Last big one and we made it to the taper! Holy smokes 

The 135 - 145 HR is solid. Finished with lunge matrix 5 reps and leg swings. Fueled Precision every 4 miles or so, caffeine at 4 and 8 miles. Gatorade and water on the trunk of the car.
Walk with Sarah  trees are looking mighty!

Felt great! Massive heart rate strap error in the first mile  Smooth sailing this next 2 weeks with a bit of quality sprinkled in. Heart rate plan for the marathon coming up soon! Finished with SAM PHASE 1

Cut this one a bit short. Let the heart rate go up way too soon. The legs were ready to go, but the heart was not prepared for this warmer temperature. We'd been running in cooler temps and the heart wasn't ready for this, but the legs were. I've got to remember to adjust if the temperature is warmer and SLOW DOWN. Perceived effort in temps above 70 should feel like I'm barely moving.

Saturday's run adjusted and made shorter also. Good to talk with Coach right as I cut the run off. Finished with lunge matrix 5 reps and leg swings.

Lunge matrix 4 reps and SAM PHASE 1

Easy does it! Legs and heart felt like they could have done the planned easy 6, but went with strength and mobility instead. Good choice

21 hour day yesterday, with 4 hours of driving. This was on 5 hours of sleep 

 Wednesday turned to be a good mistake! Felt solid during this and either my HR strap is messed up or my hear can handle higher range, because this felt like nothing! Finished with SAM PHASE 1, Lunge matrix 4 reps, and leg swings. Hydrating at foot of driveway.
Real happy with this HR. Granted it's ridiculously cool out, I'm feeling very happy with where I am leading into next Sunday! Finished with lunge matrix 3 reps.

Heart rate strap broke. I think I only had about 90 runs on it. At times it's reading 190 when I'm walking and 110 when I'm running. Glad I bought a back up. True average bpm during this was more like 120. Finished with strides and leg swings.

Feeling confident for Sunday still, but the fact even the back up strap could glitch out and give me crazy readings during the race is giving me a bit of anxiety. I'll just focus on perceived effort if that happens.
Last little bit of turning the legs over. Felt solid, especially in this temperature!
Keeping legs turning, feeling pumped!
I've got options, so going through them.

column3: Walk to the Expo with Sarah and Mom

column5: feel great!

column3: Subway and walk  to the Ferry for NYC Marathon!
column5: This is HYPE!

Will update more later! Definitely a bit too aggressive too early, but held on best I could and learned a lot about what I'd be truly capable of up to mile 22 or so and then have gas in the tank to actually push the last 4 miles.

Loved it today, and thanks for all the runs I've done with Utica Roadrunners, Sneaker Store Run Club, and Marcy Hills!
Dinner in Bed
Felt great! Good to see a bunch of awesome folks. Picked it up a bit at the end. Finished with lunge matrix 3 reps and SAM PHASE 1.

Edit: Not going 20 tomorrow 

Loosely quoting Clayton Young, quoting Kipchoge, "it's good to run some the week after the marathon and see if there's anything lingering that needs attention. Then rest more in the following weeks." Everything feels loose and fresh so far and I'm going to keep my HR 120 to 135.

I'm tempted to go longer tomorrow, very low HR. 20 probably isn't the best idea, but if the effort is minimal, why not? I think at least 10, and we'll see what happens at that point. Finished with lunge matrix 4 reps each. Very optimistic for a few weeks low intensity then maybe tune up for Lake Effect Half.

Met up with Dave, Tim, Joe, Brett, and Josh K. Nice along the canal. Good to share some of the marathon experience. First truly "cold" one of the season. Finished with lunge matrix 3 reps. Might get some miles in tomorrow with Tim again. Good luck with cross countriers and Stockadeathon runners tomorrow!

Nice and relaxing out there with Tim. Finished with leg swings. Had a bit of a side stitch off and on the past couple of days. The goal this week was basic, get some recovery running in and keep blood flowing off the marathon. Now on to more of a rest week, some biking with maybe only 2 days of running. 

Feeling very optimistic to build up aerobic volume in December.
Biked to the store to try on some sneaks. Didn't have the Metaspeeds, but tried on Pro 3s felt much better than when I didn't have as much leg and foot control

Ran, or should I say rode, into Dr. Nic! He's got the running bug after seeing some of us hit that marathon finished with lunge matrix 3 reps. Side stitch is 99% gone! Sticking to the plan of 2 or 3 days of running this week. I'm liking this recovery so far.
Was jonesin for Graffenburg. Got my fix and it felt great. Looks like all systems are go to start building aerobic volume next week! Finished with lunge matrix 4 reps.
